
## PROJECT OVERVIEW

This project, AutomaticJesse, aims to automate various tasks and workflows using AI and a role-based system.  The system utilizes a multi-role architecture for handling diverse functionalities.  Further details on project goals and scope will be added here.


## CODE STYLE

* Consistent indentation (4 spaces).
* Meaningful variable and function names.
* Adherence to PEP 8 (Python) and relevant style guides for other languages.


## FOLDER ORGANIZATION

The project follows a modular structure, separating concerns into distinct folders.  Specific folder organization is detailed in the `FOLDER_ORGANIZATION.md` file within the `.cursor/rules` directory.


## TECH STACK

* Python (version 3.9+)
* JavaScript (Node.js)
* Electron (for desktop application)
* React (for UI components)
* Tailwind CSS (for styling)
* PostgreSQL (for database)
* SQLite (added as alternative to PostgreSQL)
* pnpm (for package management)
* Other libraries and tools as needed.


## PROJECT-SPECIFIC STANDARDS

* All roles must have clearly defined responsibilities (see `.cursor/rules/system/000-role-definitions.mdc`).
* Role communication follows a predefined protocol (see `.cursor/rules/system/100-communication-protocol.mdc`).  All role communications must be properly formatted with the designated color emoji (🔵 for ES, 🟠 for SET, 🟢 for CTW, 🟣 for DES). Each role must respond appropriately when addressed. Clear separation must be maintained between different roles' communications. The last mentioned role will be tracked and used as the default responder when no specific role is addressed.  **Conflict noted:**  Failure to identify oneself by role in communication requires an audit of `.cursor/rules` files by SET.
* All code must be thoroughly tested.


## WORKFLOW & RELEASE RULES

* Agile development methodology is employed.
* Version control using Git.
* Regular release cycles will be determined and documented here.  Addressing communication protocol lapses requires auditing `.cursor/rules` files.  **Clarification:** Audits of `.cursor/rules` files to address communication protocol lapses will be conducted by SET.  The audit will also include verification of proper role identification in all communications. File access timeouts require investigation and resolution.

